original_query: Looking for HP (yes HP) laptop under $650 normal day to day. Hi, I am looking for a HP (yes HP) laptop under $650 normal day to day.... Would like it to be 15.6in screen, touch screen and at least 16gb RAM. Any suggestions would be helpful! Thanks

Looking for a 2-in-1 With Stylus Compatibility ($200 to 800 USD, US) Thank you in advance for any advice and suggestions LAPTOP QUESTIONNAIRE Total budget (in local currency) and country of purchase. Please do not use USD unless purchasing in the US: $200 to $800 US (possibly selling current laptop) Are you open to refurbs/used? Absolutely, almost preferred How would you prioritize form factor (ultrabook, 2-in-1, etc.), build quality, performance, and battery life? 2-in-1 or tablet+keyboard with stylus support and good battery life (7+ hrs, open to undervolting) How important is weight and thinness to you? Really only light enough to not collapse a music stand Do you have a preferred screen size? If indifferent, put N/A. Under 16in Are you doing any CAD/video editing/photo editing/gaming? List which programs/games you desire to run. Light gaming (Terraria is the heaviest I've played recently) If you're gaming, do you have certain games you want to play? At what settings and FPS do you want? Same as prev - 1080p 60, medium or higher settings Any specific requirements such as good keyboard, reliable build quality, touch-screen, finger-print reader, optical drive or good input devices (keyboard/touchpad) Stylus support (i.e. Surface pen, Galaxy sPen, etc.) Nub if Thinkpad USBC charging capable Leave any finishing thoughts here that you may feel are necessary and beneficial to the discussion. I am a college student, and I mostly use my laptop for homework, doc writing, and browsing. I also have a dreadfully slow tablet for note-taking and sheet music that I would like to replace. I bought my current laptop expecting to play heavy games or use CAD software often, but neither have happened in the year+ since I bought it. I may look to sell my current laptop ( for ~$750-800 hopefully, if I do sell) Asus Vivobook Pro 15 with Intel Ultra 7 and RTX 3050 I am reasonably software-savvy and open to experimenting and tinkering for things like battery life and power efficiency I use Linux Debian and Mint

All-around Premium Ultrabook with Specific Requests Laptop Request US LAPTOP QUESTIONNAIRE Total budget (in local currency) and country of purchase. Please do not use USD unless purchasing in the US: $4000 USD Are you open to refurbs/used? No. How would you prioritize form factor (ultrabook, 2-in-1, etc.), build quality, performance, and battery life? My order of the above factors is: battery life, build quality, form factor (ultrabook), performance. All of these are secondary to my specific requirements expanded upon in the second to last question. How important is weight and thinness to you? Very important. Ideally, the laptop should be under 3lbs and less than 0.7 inches thick. Do you have a preferred screen size? If indifferent, put N/A. Prefer 14 inches or smaller. Can go up to 14.5 inches. Are you doing any CAD/video editing/photo editing/gaming? List which programs/games you desire to run. This laptop will be an all-arounder but the most intensive tasks would be compiling large codebases, running multiple docker containers and VMs, editing photos and videos (not professionally), and possibly large file copies for backups. If you're gaming, do you have certain games you want to play? At what settings and FPS do you want? N/A. The only game I play is OSRS and I'm sure I can do that on any laptop. Any specific requirements such as good keyboard, reliable build quality, touch-screen, finger-print reader, optical drive or good input devices (keyboard/touchpad)? Must haves: Intel CPU, 32GB RAM, 2x USB 4, 2x USB-A 3.2 Gen2, 2x m.2 NVMe slots (prefer 2280 but can live with one being 2230). Nice to haves (in order): SD card reader (micro or full), smart card reader, 64GB RAM, Ethernet, HDMI, aux, built-in webcam and microphone, fingerprint reader. Leave any finishing thoughts here that you may feel are necessary and beneficial to the discussion. I appreciate the help! I know something like this may not exist but figured I'd check to see if anyone knows of any unicorn laptops that I don't. I already have some options in mind which meet some but not all of my must haves so I'm really keenly focused on hearing from you all on things which would meet all of the must haves.
